Traditional university teaching methods can, in principle,
support most aspects of learning:

learning activity  supported by
-----------------  --------------------------
acquisition        lectures and reading
practice           exercises and problems
discussion         seminars and tutorials
discovery          field trips and practicals

but feedback is lacking.
It tends to be slow, unreliable, and extrinsic.

> > Teaching is a sort of conversation.
>
> --- Ramsden 1992:168

so we must make a special effort to ensure the two sides
do not talk past one another.

She identifies four dialogue forms:

> Discursive:
> :   *  teachers' and students' conceptions are accessible to the other
>        and the topic goal is negotiable
>     *  students must be able to generate and receive feedback on descriptions
>        appropriate to the topic goal;
>     *  the teacher must be able to reflect on studentâ€™s descriptions
>        and adjust their own descriptions to be more meaningful to the student.
> Adaptive:
> :   *  the teacher can use the relationship between their own and the studentâ€™s conception
>        to set up and adapt a task environment for the continuing dialogue,
>        in the light of the topic goals;
>     *  the student must be able to use their existing conceptual knowledge
>        to adapt their actions in the task environment in order to achieve the task goal.
> Interactive:
> :   *  the students can act within the task environment to achieve the task goal;
>     *  they should receive meaningful intrinsic feedback on their actions
